   <abstract >Inclusiveness has emerged as a notably significant topic within the realm of Human Resource Management (HRM), particularly in public and non-profit organizations (Riccucci, 2021). The rationale behind this growing focus is the recognition that these sectors serve diverse populations and require a workforce that not only reflects but also comprehends this diversity. Despite the recognized importance of diversity in HRM, organizations persistently struggle with including various employee needs while implementing the HRM policies, resulting in enduring inequalities and the underrepresentation of certain groups in the workplace. In light of these challenges and complexities, this dissertation delves into the under-subscribed benefits affecting underrepresented groups in public and non-profit organizations. Each essay examines the realms of employment, wage distribution, work arrangements, and retention within public and non-profit entities. Through this equity perspective, the dissertation aims to highlight the disparities and obstacles that impede the creation of inclusive workplaces. The introductory sections offer a detailed overview of these inequality subjects, shedding light on the root causes and suggesting potential strategies to cultivate a more equitable and diverse workforce.</abstract>
